---
import SiteShell from "../components/SiteShell.astro"
---

<SiteShell
  title="Devbox"
  description="Devbox keeps a shared code folder continuous across machines, backed by the Loom sync engine direction."
>
  <section class="hero">
    <div class="hero-copy">
      <p class="eyebrow">Folder continuity for developers</p>
      <h1>Your code folder, already there.</h1>
      <p>
        Devbox is for the moment you open another machine and the folder you
        trust is ready: source, context, machine state, and enough local bytes
        to keep moving.
      </p>
      <div class="hero-actions">
        <a class="button primary" href="/auth/sign-in">Open dashboard</a>
        <a class="button secondary" href="/docs/">Read the alpha docs</a>
      </div>
    </div>
    <figure class="hero-media">
      <img
        src="/devbox-folder-continuity.png"
        alt="Two laptops showing the same code folder across machines"
        width="1536"
        height="864"
      />
      <figcaption class="hero-caption">
        Same folder, different machine, with Devbox tracking what is local,
        cached, or remote-only.
      </figcaption>
    </figure>
  </section>

  <section class="section band" id="continuity">
    <div class="section-heading">
      <p class="eyebrow">Shared folders</p>
      <h2>The folder is the product boundary.</h2>
      <p>
        A shared folder can hold one repo, many repos, no repo, nested apps,
        secrets, dependencies, generated files, and agent work. Devbox treats
        that as normal developer life instead of asking the user to clean it up
        first.
      </p>
    </div>
    <div class="grid">
      <article class="feature-card">
        <h3>Capture file versions often</h3>
        <p>
          Loom records individual file states frequently, then coalesces stable
          folder revisions at sync, restore, checkpoint, and merge boundaries.
        </p>
      </article>
      <article class="feature-card">
        <h3>Restore a coherent tree</h3>
        <p>
          Folder revisions describe a complete view of the tree without turning
          every edit into a whole-folder snapshot.
        </p>
      </article>
      <article class="feature-card">
        <h3>Trust messy folders</h3>
        <p>
          Devbox keeps user intent centered on folders while the engine handles
          object storage, cache metadata, and future chunk transfer.
        </p>
      </article>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section" id="machines">
    <div class="split">
      <div class="section-heading">
        <p class="eyebrow">Machines</p>
        <h2>Move between computers without rebuilding context.</h2>
        <p>
          Machines are first-class in Devbox. Each machine needs a clear cursor,
          a known hydration state, and a trusted auth boundary before it can
          materialize or update a shared folder.
        </p>
        <div class="section-actions">
          <a class="button primary" href="/dashboard">View app route</a>
          <a class="button secondary" href="/docs/getting-started/">
            Alpha setup
          </a>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="signal-list">
        <article class="signal">
          <h3>Cursor clarity</h3>
          <p>
            Machine, remote, and materialized-folder cursors explain what each
            side believes is current.
          </p>
        </article>
        <article class="signal">
          <h3>Checkpoint intent</h3>
          <p>
            Human labels and pins help users retain meaningful folder revisions
            without managing object internals.
          </p>
        </article>
        <article class="signal">
          <h3>Sandbox work</h3>
          <p>
            Humans and agents need isolated parallel workspaces that can merge
            back into a trusted shared folder.
          </p>
        </article>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section band" id="storage">
    <div class="section-heading">
      <p class="eyebrow">Sparse and lazy storage</p>
      <h2>Know which bytes are here before pretending they are.</h2>
      <p>
        The alpha documents the direction without claiming sparse clone is
        complete: cache entries record object byte availability separately from
        file versions and folder revisions.
      </p>
    </div>
    <div class="timeline">
      <div class="step">
        <span>Remote-only</span>
        <p>Metadata is known, but the object bytes are not local yet.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="step">
        <span>Partial</span>
        <p>Some bytes are available while future chunk transfer fills gaps.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="step">
        <span>Fully local</span>
        <p>The cache can serve the object without remote reads.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="step">
        <span>Pinned</span>
        <p>Retention intent keeps important revisions from being pruned.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section" id="loom">
    <div class="grid">
      <article class="feature-card">
        <h3>Devbox is the product</h3>
        <p>
          The user should think in folders and machines, not protocol details or
          Git-only workflows.
        </p>
      </article>
      <article class="feature-card">
        <h3>Loom is the engine direction</h3>
        <p>
          Loom is the deeper sync and source-control model underneath Devbox:
          objects, file versions, revisions, cursors, and cache records.
        </p>
      </article>
      <article class="feature-card">
        <h3>Git still matters</h3>
        <p>
          Devbox respects today&apos;s repos, but it is not built around Git as
          the only shape a folder can take.
        </p>
      </article>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section band" id="trust">
    <div class="split">
      <div class="section-heading">
        <p class="eyebrow">Trust and safety</p>
        <h2>Continuity is only useful when the boundary is clear.</h2>
        <p>
          Devbox needs plain behavior around secrets, generated files,
          authentication, sparse storage caveats, and what is safe to hydrate on
          a new machine.
        </p>
      </div>
      <div class="signal-list">
        <article class="signal">
          <h3>Secrets deserve policy</h3>
          <p>
            Secret detection and block policies should stop unsafe captures
            before object writes.
          </p>
        </article>
        <article class="signal">
          <h3>Auth stays server-owned</h3>
          <p>
            Browser code should not pass WorkOS access tokens directly to the
            hosted Devbox API.
          </p>
        </article>
        <article class="signal">
          <h3>Generated files need intent</h3>
          <p>
            Dependencies, caches, build output, and local overlays are useful,
            but they should not blur the trusted source boundary.
          </p>
        </article>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section" id="agents">
    <div class="split">
      <div class="section-heading">
        <p class="eyebrow">Developers and agents</p>
        <h2>Parallel work should not damage the folder people trust.</h2>
        <p>
          Devbox is heading toward sandboxes for human and agent work, with
          merge points that make folder state, overlays, and machine identity
          explicit.
        </p>
      </div>
      <form class="contact-form" aria-label="Alpha waitlist form">
        <div class="field">
          <label for="email">Work email</label>
          <input id="email" name="email" type="email" autocomplete="email" />
        </div>
        <div class="field">
          <label for="folder">What folder should Devbox help with?</label>
          <textarea id="folder" name="folder"></textarea>
        </div>
        <button class="button primary" type="button"
          >Request alpha access</button
        >
        <p class="form-note">
          Form boundary: this PR ships the UI only. Wire this to an API, CRM, or
          mail action before collecting submissions.
        </p>
      </form>
    </div>
  </section>
</SiteShell>
